    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">ISOLATION OF HUMAN FETAL LIVER STEM CELLS AND CHARACTERIZATION BY RT-PCR</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">PALANIAPPAN S</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">ISOLATION OF HUMAN FETAL LIVER, STEM CELLS, CHARACTERIZATION, RT-PCR</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">1-Apr-2008 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM UNIVERSITY</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">4105</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The liver is the largest organ in the human body and it is considered as
chemical factory of the body. Its functions includes: metabolism of carbohydrates,
fats, proteins, Nucleic acids, vitamins and hormones in addition to secreting bile and
detoxification. It also maintains the balance between cell gain and cell loss through
normal proliferative quiescent of hepatocytes.
Liver injuries can activate the potential cell compartment located
within the intra hepatic bilary tree giving rise to bipotent cells called oval cells within
the lobules that can differentiate into hepatocytic and bilary epithelial cells. During
the development process, the architecture of mature liver becomes apparent with the
differentiation of hepatoblast which are defined as precursors for hepatocytic as well
as bilary ductal cells. Universal definition of liver stem cells has not been assigned
till now but however according to “Potten &amp; Loeffter” these are defined as
undifferentiated, self-maintaining (self renewing), and pluripotent - capable of
repopulating the liver and flexible in expressing these previous characteristics. Liver
stem cells provide insights into the potential pathways involving liver regeneration
that is independent of mature hepatocytes. Hepatic progenitor cells are either bipotent
or multipotent and capable of multiple round of replication. They have been identified
in fetal as well as adult liver
The hepatic/stem progenitor cell involves the development of an
alternative therapy to liver transplantation for patients with liver failure. There are
currently more than 17,000 people on the waiting list for a liver transplantation, with
the majority of the patients suffering with cirrhosis - a manifestation of chronic liver
injury associated with Hepatitis-B, Hepatitis-C and chronic alcoholism. Using
hepatocytic or hepatic progenitor cells as cellular therapy to replace damaged liver
could potentially help alternative some of the challenges in solid organ
transplantation.
Click here to buy
ABBYY PDF Transformer 2.0
www.ABBYY.com
Click here to buy
ABBYY PDF Transformer 2.0
www.ABBYY.com
An additional and often times greater challenge when working with
stem cell is the lack of unique markers to identify these cells. Although some markers
are observed in stem cell subsets, stem cells are routinely characterized by the absence
rather than the presence of specific lineage related markers. In liver we can find more
than 90 genes. Most of the genes will be expressed in both fetal and adult stages such
as Alcohol dehydrogenase, Aldose B, Alpha fibrinogen, Antithrombin, Anion
exchanger, Biliary glycoprotein, Dipeptidase, Cysteine dioxygenase, Alpha
fetoprotein, Albumin, Cytokeratin-18, Cytokeratin-19 etc., But some genes will be
expressed in fetal stage only, where some other genes will be expressed in adult stage
only. Some gene predominantly expressed in fetal liver and in adult at very negligible
amount only. Some of the liver specific genes are:
Alpha fetoprotein (AFP) is a protein produced in the developing
embryo and fetus. In human, AFP level decrease gradually after birth, reaching adult
levels by 8 to 12 months. Normal adult AFP level are low, but detectable.
Albumin, a group of proteins including serum and together constituting
roughly 60% of the protein in Plasma. Albumin is important in regulating blood
volume by maintaining the osmotic pressure of blood compartment and for
transporting fatty acids, thyroid hormones, some steroid hormones, and other
substances in the bloodstream.
Cytokeratins are intermediate filament keratins found in the
intracytoplasmic cytoskeleton of epithelial tissue. There are two types of cytokeratins:
the low weights acidic type I cytokeratins and the high weight basic or neutral type II
cytokeratins. Cytokeratins are usually found in pairs comprising Albumin and Alphafetoprotein
which are hepatocytic markers and cytokeratin acts as bilary cell markers.</td></tr>
